<a href="http://www.eu2013.lt/en/news/pressreleases/the-lithuanian-presidency-intends-to-reach-a-full-general-approach-on-the-european-maritime-and-fisheries-fund" target="_self">http://www.eu2013.lt/en/news/pressreleases/the-lithuanian-presidency-int...</a></p><p>CFP Reform Watch, ‘Slim majority for vessel construction aid in fisheries committee’, 10&nbsp;July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://cfp-reformwatch.eu/2013/07/slim-majority-for-vessel-construction-aid-in-fisheries-committee/" target="_self">http://cfp-reformwatch.eu/2013/07/slim-majority-for-vessel-construction-...</a></p><p>Europêche-Cogeca position on EP compromise amendments to the proposal for a regulation of the EMFF, 5&nbsp;July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.europeche.org/images/stories/video/EP63rev_Position_on_Compromise_Amendments_to_the_EMFF_EN.pdf" target="_self">http://www.europeche.org/images/stories/video/EP63rev_Position_on_Compro...</a></p><p><i>Undercurrent News</i>, ‘Green lobby outrage over EU vessel-building aid’, 10&nbsp;July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.undercurrentnews.com/2013/07/10/green-lobby-outrage-over-eu-vessel-building-aid/#.UeO0nKRV1Mt" target="_self">http://www.undercurrentnews.com/2013/07/10/green-lobby-outrage-over-eu-v...</a></p><p>Oceana: European fisheries subsidies, fact sheet, ‘State aid: The hidden subsidies’, July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://oceana.org/sites/default/files/euo/OCEANA_State_aid_factsheet_072013.pdf" target="_self">http://oceana.org/sites/default/files/euo/OCEANA_State_aid_factsheet_072...</a></p><p><i>Fish Information and Services</i>, ‘Spain to receive “consistent aids with its role in EU fisheries”’, 17&nbsp;July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?monthyear=&amp;day=17&amp;id=62263&amp;l=e&amp;special=&amp;ndb=1%20target" target="_self">http://fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?monthyear=&amp;day=17&amp;id=...</a>=</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The outcome of the negotiations on the EMFF will undoubtedly influence the EU position in international forums, such as the WTO, on subsidies for building up new (small-scale) vessels or modernising them. Any increased flexibility might change the EU’s position on special and differentiated treatment for small-scale fisheries, a topic of great importance for many developing states, including ACP countries. Another element that needs to be carefully monitored by ACP countries in this debate is the political will of some member states, and some member states’ MEPs – France and Spain in particular – to push for both building subsidies and increasing funds to the outermost regions, some of which are ACP countries’ neighbours (La Reunion, Mayotte, Guadeloupe, Canary Islands, etc). If subsidies for new vessels were to be reinstated, and such funding channelled to the EU outermost regions, it could result in an increase in fishing capacity. In some cases, where EU outermost regions’ fleets operate outside their exclusive economic zones (EEZ), this might increase competition with existing fleets operating in ACP waters.</p>
		</div>
		
